{
  "What is sublimation?": "",
  "The change from liquid to gas by heating a substance to its boiling point": "",
  "The change from solid directly to gas without passing through liquid first": "",
  "The change from gas directly to liquid by cooling a substance down rapidly": "",
  "The change from liquid to solid when a substance reaches its freezing point": "",
  "Sublimation is the phase change where a solid transforms directly into a gas without first becoming a liquid. Dry ice (solid CO2) is a common example.": "",
  "What is deposition?": "",
  "The change from gas directly to solid without becoming a liquid first": "",
  "The change from solid to liquid by adding heat energy to the substance": "",
  "The change from gas to liquid when the temperature drops below boiling": "",
  "The change from liquid to gas that happens at the surface of a liquid": "",
  "Deposition is the reverse of sublimation — a gas changes directly into a solid without first becoming a liquid. Frost forming on a cold window is a common example.": "",
  "Which of the following is an everyday example of sublimation?": "",
  "Ice cubes melting in a glass of warm lemonade": "",
  "Water boiling in a pot on the kitchen stove top": "",
  "Dry ice producing a fog without leaving any liquid": "",
  "Rain falling from clouds down to the ground below": "",
  "Dry ice (solid carbon dioxide) sublimes at room temperature — it goes directly from a solid to a gas, creating a foggy effect without ever forming a liquid puddle.": "",
  "Frost forming on a cold window on a winter morning is an example of which phase change?": "",
  "Sublimation": "",
  "Condensation": "",
  "Evaporation": "",
  "Deposition": "",
  "Frost forms when water vapor in the air changes directly into ice crystals on a cold surface — gas to solid. This is deposition, the reverse of sublimation.": "",
  "During sublimation, does the substance pass through the liquid state?": "",
  "Yes, it briefly becomes a liquid before turning into a gas": "",
  "No, it goes directly from solid to gas skipping the liquid": "",
  "Yes, the liquid stage lasts for a very long period of time": "",
  "No, it goes directly from gas to solid skipping the liquid": "",
  "In sublimation, the substance transforms directly from solid to gas without ever becoming a liquid. The particles gain enough energy to break free completely from the solid structure.": "",
  "What substance is commonly used to demonstrate sublimation in classrooms?": "",
  "Table salt crystals": "",
  "Liquid nitrogen tanks": "",
  "Dry ice (solid CO2)": "",
  "Regular ice cubes": "",
  "Dry ice (solid carbon dioxide) is the classic example of sublimation. At normal atmospheric pressure, it converts directly from solid to gas at -78.5 degrees C.": "",
  "What happens to the energy of particles during sublimation?": "",
  "Particles lose energy and slow down during this process": "",
  "Particles gain energy and break free from the solid form": "",
  "Particle energy stays exactly the same the entire time here": "",
  "Particles are destroyed and reformed as gas molecules now": "",
  "During sublimation, particles absorb enough energy to completely overcome the intermolecular forces holding them in the solid structure, transitioning directly to the gas phase.": "",
  "Is energy absorbed or released during deposition?": "",
  "Energy is absorbed by the particles during deposition": "",
  "Energy is released by the particles during deposition": "",
  "No energy change occurs at all during the deposition": "",
  "Energy is both absorbed and released in equal amounts": "",
  "During deposition, gas particles lose energy as they slow down and form a solid. The particles release energy to their surroundings as they lock into fixed positions.": "",
