  "Melting into a liquid that evaporates away slowly": "",
  "Decomposition into different chemical compounds entirely": "",
  "Sublimation from solid directly into gas without melting": "",
  "Dissolving into the surrounding air moisture over months": "",
  "Mothballs are made of naphthalene or paradichlorobenzene, which slowly sublime at room temperature. The solid gradually converts directly to gas, causing the mothball to shrink and eventually disappear.": "",
  "Can regular water ice undergo sublimation?": "",
  "No, water ice can only melt into liquid water when heated": "",
  "Yes, ice can sublime especially in dry, cold, low-pressure conditions": "",
  "No, only dry ice can undergo sublimation, not regular water ice": "",
  "Yes, but only when heated above 100 degrees Celsius and pressurized": "",
  "Yes, water ice can sublime. This commonly happens with snow and ice in dry, cold conditions — the ice slowly disappears without melting. Freeze-dried food relies on this principle.": "",
  "What is a phase change?": "",
  "A transformation of a substance from one state of matter to another state": "",
  "A chemical reaction that changes one substance into a completely different one": "",
  "The process of dissolving a solid substance in a liquid to form a solution": "",
  "A change in the color of a substance caused by exposure to sunlight or heat": "",
  "A phase change is a physical change where a substance transitions between states of matter — such as solid, liquid, or gas — without changing its chemical identity.": "",
  "What does 'endothermic' mean?": "",
  "A process that releases energy into the surroundings as heat": "",
  "A process that absorbs energy from the surroundings as heat": "",
  "A process that has no energy change happening at any point": "",
  "A process that both absorbs and releases equal energy amounts": "",
  "An endothermic process absorbs energy from the surroundings. Sublimation is endothermic because the solid must absorb heat energy to transform directly into a gas.": "",
  "What does 'exothermic' mean?": "",
  "A process where energy is absorbed from the surrounding environment": "",
  "A process where energy is released into the surrounding environment": "",
  "A process where no energy is transferred in any direction at all": "",
  "A process that only occurs at absolute zero degrees on the Kelvin scale": "",
  "An exothermic process releases energy into the surroundings. Deposition is exothermic because gas particles release energy as they slow down and form a solid.": "",
  "What does 'freeze-drying' mean?": "",
  "Cooling a substance until it freezes and then storing it in a cold place": "",
  "Removing water from frozen material by sublimation under low pressure": "",
  "Heating a substance to evaporate all the water and then cooling it down": "",
  "Mixing a substance with dry ice so that it absorbs the cold temperature": "",
  "Freeze-drying involves freezing a substance and then reducing the pressure so the frozen water sublimes directly from solid ice to water vapor, preserving the material.": "",
  "What does 'water vapor' mean?": "",
  "Water in its gaseous state that is invisible in the air around us": "",
  "Tiny visible droplets of liquid water floating as clouds or steam": "",
  "Solid ice crystals that form on surfaces during very cold weather": "",
  "A chemical compound different from regular liquid water molecules": "",
  "Water vapor is the gaseous form of water. It is an invisible gas present in the atmosphere. Visible steam or clouds are actually tiny liquid water droplets, not true water vapor.": "",
  "What is dry ice?": "",
  "Regular frozen water that has been dehydrated in a special process": "",
  "Solid carbon dioxide that sublimes at normal atmospheric pressure": "",
  "A type of ice that forms only in extremely dry desert environments": "",
  "Frozen nitrogen gas used for cooling in scientific lab experiments": "",
  "Dry ice is solid carbon dioxide (CO2). It is called 'dry' because it sublimes directly into gas at -78.5 degrees C under normal pressure, leaving no liquid behind.": "",
  "What does 'intermolecular forces' mean in the context of phase changes?": "",
  "The forces within an atom that hold the nucleus together in place": "",
  "The attractive forces between separate molecules that affect state": "",
  "The forces of gravity acting on molecules pulling them downward": "",
  "The magnetic forces that only exist between metal atoms in solids": "",
  "Intermolecular forces are the attractive forces between separate molecules. During sublimation, particles must gain enough energy to completely overcome these forces and escape as gas.": "",
  "What does 'vapor pressure' mean?": "",
  "The pressure inside a container that has been completely emptied of all gas": "",
  "The pressure exerted by vapor molecules above a solid or liquid surface": "",
  "The force needed to compress a gas into a much smaller container space": "",
  "The temperature at which a liquid starts to boil and turn into a gas form": "",
  "Vapor pressure is the pressure exerted by the gas molecules that have escaped from a solid or liquid surface. It plays a role in sublimation and evaporation rates.": "",
  "What is a 'phase diagram'?": "",
  "A graph showing the states of a substance at different temperatures and pressures": "",
  "A drawing of the arrangement of atoms inside a single molecule of a substance": "",
  "A table listing all of the chemical properties of a substance in one location": "",
  "A chart showing the results of a chemistry experiment performed in a lab class": "",
  "A phase diagram is a graph that shows which state of matter (solid, liquid, or gas) a substance exists in at various combinations of temperature and pressure.": "",
  "What does 'triple point' mean on a phase diagram?": "",
  "The specific temperature and pressure where all three states of matter can coexist": "",
  "The temperature at which a substance reaches three times its normal boiling point": "",
  "The point where three different substances combine together to form one compound": "",
  "The pressure at which a gas can no longer be compressed any further in a container": "",
  "The triple point is the unique combination of temperature and pressure at which a substance can exist as a solid, liquid, and gas simultaneously.": "",
  "A student leaves wet clothes outside on a freezing day. By evening, the clothes are dry even though the temperature stayed below freezing. What happened?": "",
  "The water melted and then evaporated very quickly in the cold wind": "",
  "The frozen water sublimed directly from ice to water vapor in the air": "",
  "The clothes absorbed all the water back into the fabric permanently": "",
  "Wind blew the ice crystals off the clothes and scattered them away": "",
  "The ice in the clothes sublimed — it changed directly from solid ice to water vapor without melting first. This can happen in dry, cold conditions with low humidity and wind.": "",
  "Astronauts use freeze-dried food in space. Why is sublimation useful for preserving food?": "",
  "It adds chemicals to the food that prevent bacteria from growing inside it": "",
  "It removes water without high heat, preserving the food's nutrients and structure": "",
  "It cooks the food at a very high temperature that kills all living organisms in it": "",
  "It compresses the food into a small size so it takes up less storage space overall": "",
  "Freeze-drying removes water by sublimation at low temperatures and pressures. This preserves the food's shape, nutrients, and flavor much better than heat-based drying methods.": "",
  "On a cold morning, you see ice crystals (frost) on the windshield of a car. Where did the water come from?": "",
  "Rain fell during the night and froze on the windshield surface": "",
  "Water vapor in the air deposited directly as ice on the cold glass": "",
  "The glass itself released moisture that then froze on the outside": "",
  "Dew formed first as liquid, then was frozen by the morning air": "",
  "Frost forms by deposition — water vapor in the air changes directly into solid ice crystals when it contacts the very cold windshield surface, skipping the liquid phase.": "",
